collection.description: This collection features our conversations throughout the State of Maine held with educators, students, community members, and major Maine industry professionals. We are asking what youth will need to thrive personally, civically, and economically in the Maine of 2050. The collection is expanding daily, so check back!
collection.title: Maine ED 2050

highlights.description: If you don't build a relationship between yourself and students/other staff members, respect won't happen. Learning won't happen if you don't have that respect.
People, staff/students/admin, need to be willing to do their job. Step in and help others. It might not be perfect, but if the effort if there, we will be successful.
Relationships are so critical to a student's success.
This goes back to the importance of building relationships, letting students know we care about them, not just their education, but them as people.
What students value through high school will more than likely change in adulthood.
Need a support system from the bottom to the top. Make it clear to students we are there for them. We don't always have to agree with everything, but can still be supportive.
Important to note that our students come from so many different backgrounds. We have a large student population that does not have their basic needs met. That plays a big role in education.
It's important to be present. Just knowing someone is there, a person in your corner, is important in education.
Need to have support, from home and at school.
This plays off of my point of how important relationships are. Not all students have strong, dependable relationships at home, and that makes the relationships at school even more important.

We need to tap into students' potential. What are they interested in? It makes me think of vocational trades. Are we providing those opportunities for kids? Success doesn't look the same for all kids.
Students (and staff) have been resilient and flexible with the unpredictability of the world in the past couple of years. We are all doing a good job, and have to remember that.
How do we continue to drive technological innovation forward as a positive, and how do we remedy the negative implications?
We have technology at our fingertips, but not used to being patient. Sometimes it's ok to slow down.
Kids are overall more accepting of diversity than they were a decade or more ago.
Job skills like interviewing are important.
Financial literacy is not taught but so important.
Do our students have skills in communication face-to-face. They become so reliant on technology.
For some students, just showing up is tough enough. There is a lot of outside factors that students deal with and for them to just be here and be present, we need to recognize that.
Mental health needs to become a focus - managing of big emotions.

Students have the great ability to challenge us, teachers/staff. To question what we have to say, make us feel uncomfortable, which isn't always bad. We can be stuck in our ways, but it's important for us to learn from the students, not just them learning from us.
Being able to set and monitor goals is an important life skill.
Students need to learn respect of others and self.
Students are more accepting of others than they may have been 10 years ago.
Keeps need to learn accountability. They often feel like there will be a second chance for them.
Students seem be more open to each other and wanting to learn about each others differences.

Students missed a significant amount of learning due to the pandemic. Some students were able to bounce back quickly, but a lot of students without support at home and with other obstacles fell further behind. How do we address classrooms where the knowledge gaps are so large? It makes it extremely hard for teachers and students.
Failure is a learning opportunity, not a negative thing. You can learn when you fail, and accepting that can be extremely positive.
Controlling your emotions can be huge. We can all be different, but being confident in who you are and accepting others can help you control your emotions.
Students would benefit from other programs that would help prepare them for work after high school.
Respecting yourself/knowing yourself with help with relationships.
Strong communities build strong education systems.
We have to stop comparing what life used to be like. Meet kids where they are at, give them the respect with the time they are growing up.

Every year, every class, every student will be different. We can't always just do the same thing year after year. We as adults need to adapt and help our students where they are. We as adults need to be respected as professionals and let us decide what is best for our students.
